Ma , Z. , Richard , H. , and Foster , J.W. ( 2003 ) pH-dependent modulation of cyclic AMP levels and GadW-dependent repression of RpoS affect synthesis of the GadX regulator and Escherichia coli acid resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17919280" target="_blank">17919280</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_20", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Ma , Z. , Richard , H. , and Foster , J.W. ( 2003b ) pH-dependent modulation of cyclic AMP levels and GadW-dependent repression of RpoS affect synthesis of the GadX regulator and Escherichia coli acid resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li></div>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_22">
Sodium regulates Escherichia coli acid resistance , and inﬂuences GadX - and GadW-dependent activation of gadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19861135" target="_blank">19861135</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_22", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Richard , H. , and Foster , J.W. ( 2007 ) Sodium regulates Escherichia coli acid resistance , and inﬂuences GadX - and GadW-dependent activation of gadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>Richard , H. and Foster , J.W. ( 2007 ) Sodium regulates Escherichia coli acid resistance , and inﬂuences GadX - and GadW-dependent activation of gadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20189963" target="_blank">20189963</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>The inability of GadX to induce yhiE might explain its lack of acid resistance induction in exponentially growing cells .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>Not only CarA and CarB , but also GadX and GadC , are required for acid resistance , for maintenance of the intracellular pH homeostasis under external acidic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17919280" target="_blank">17919280</a>]<br></li>
<li>Acid resistance appears to contribute to the low infectious dose of pathogenic E. col and aids the gastric passage of commensal strains .28,29 One of the most efﬁcient acid resistance systems in E. coli , the Gad system , is based on the coordinated action of two isoforms of glutamate decarboxylase ( GadA and GadB ) and of a speciﬁc glutamate/gamma-aminobutyrate antiporter ( GadC ) .30,31 The gadA/BC genes , activated in response to acid stress and in stationary phase cells , are subject to complex circuits of regulation involving the AraC-family regulator GadX .32 In this study , we show that GadX contributes to multi-drug resistance as well as acid resistance in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>]<br></li>
<li>Identiﬁcation of the effectors involved in GadX activation and further investigation of the interactions between regulatory components of the gad system ( H-NS , RpoS , CRP , and GadX ) may provide further insight into the molecular circuitry underlying the glutamic acid-based acid stress response of E. coli A. Tramonti and P. Visca contributed equally to this work .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such an autoregulatory loop would imply that expression of both GadA and GadX is coordinated and responsible for superinduction of the whole gad system ; primary stimuli ( stationary phase and acid ) acting on PgadX would lead to increased expression of GadX and , in turn , to an ampliﬁcation of the response through GadX-de-pendent activation of the gadAX and gadBC promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , the gadBC operon coding for both components ( glutamic acid decarboxylase and cognate antiporter ) , necessary for gad system functioning , is more stimulated than gadA by GadX , thereby providing a prompt response to the acid stress .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , gadE-mtdEF belongs to the AFI and was shown to be controlled by GadX and GadW ( Kobayashi et al. , 2006 ; Sayed et al. , 2007 ) , while ybaST is not included in the AFI but is known to be signiﬁcantly induced under acidic conditions and to belong to the GadX -- GadW regulon ( Tucker et al. , 2002 ; 2003 ; Hommais et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>12.38 -8.24 -59.96 1.13 ± 0.55 ± 0.50 ± 0.02 0.04 0.02 1.27 ± 0.50 ± 0.20 ± 0.03 0.03 0.03 / h ) / h ) Fig. 2 Comparison of the transcript levels of the E. coli wild type under different pH values at 7.0 and 6.0 : a global regulatory genes , b PhoB regulatory genes , c acid-inducible genes , d metabolic pathway genes , e respiratory chain genes during micro-aerobic continuous culture at the dilution rate of 0.1 h -1 Fig. 3 a , b Overall metabolic regulation of the E. coli during acidic condition ( a ) Acid Condition Hns ATP ADP PhoQ PhoQ P ATP ADP ¬ EvgS EvgS P cAMP - evgA Pho P PhoP Crp EvgA P B1500 EvgA cAMP-Crp ¬ RpoS b1500 ydeo ¬ YdeO gadE GadE O O GadW GadX hdeA gadB gadc gadW gadA gadX HdeA GadA GadB GadC Acid resistance ( b ) Acidic Condition ( H + ) ( indirect ) EnvZ PhoR fnr OxyR ldhA arcA P Fnr ArcA SoxR / S L PhoR - P OmpR OmpR - P DH pfl yfiD ompC TCA cycle genes : gltA sdhC mdh sodA PhoB - P PhoB Lactate OmpC ompF asr YfiD Pfl OmpF Asr Formate Acetate ackA pta Acid resistance Moreover , in accord with the proteomic analysis , the expression of yﬁD : : lac reporter fusion and the intracellular content of YﬁD were found to be high during growth at low pH for both aerobic and anaerobic cultures ( Neil et al. 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23274360" target="_blank">23274360</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , in the present study , we ﬁrst examined whether previously identiﬁed regulators , such as EvgA , YdeO , MnmE , GadE , GadX , and H-NS , also participate in the anaerobic activation of mdtEF .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , except for mnmE , deletion of the regulators previously shown to participate in the regulation of mdtEF under aerobic condition , such as EvgA , YdeO , GadE , and GadX , caused no or only a moderate decrease ( 17 -- 40 % ) of the transcription of PgadE-lacZ , and deletion of H-NS caused a moderate increase of PgadE-lacZ activity , suggesting that these regulators are not responsible for the activation of mdtEF under anaerobic condition .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Involvement of EvgA , YdeO , H-NS , CRP , GadX , as well as a small RNA DsrA in the regulation of the mdtEF gene in the same operon has also been reported ( Nishino and Yamaguchi , 2002 , 2004 ; Oshima et al. , 2006 ; Nishino et al. , 2008a , b , 2009 , 2011 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include the EvgA-YdeO-GadE feed forward regulatory loop which is effective in minimal glucose medium under aerobic condition ( Ma et al. , 2004 ) , the conditional activation of the operon in a MnmE dependent manner in LB containing glucose ( LBG ) ( Gong et al. , 2004 ) , as well as the GadX or GadW dependent activation which functions primarily in rich media in stationary growth-phase ( Sayed et al. , 2007 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX binds to the gadE control region Regulators EvgA , YdeO and GadE bind to subfragments of the 798 bp gadE upstream control region ( Ma et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Regulation of gadE expression involves such regulators as EvgA , YdeO , GadE , PhoP , TrmE , GadX , and GadW ( 12 , 21 , 24 , 30 , 33 ) , which makes GadE the center of regulation for the induction of acid resistance .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21193607" target="_blank">21193607</a>]<br></li>
<li>More than ten transcription regulators including EvgA , YdeO , GadE , TorR , H-NS , PhoP , RpoS , CRP , MnmE , GadX , and GadW have been found to participate in the regulation of gadE during various circumstances of acid stresses through at least ﬁve different regulatory circuits ( Ma et al. , 2004 ; Sayed and Foster , 2009 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>INVOLVEMENT OF DIFFERENT REGULATORS IN THE ANAEROBIC EXPRESSION OF mdtEF FROM THAT OF AEROBIC CONDITION Previous studies focusing on the expression of gadE-mdtEF operon during acid resistance have revealed that several regulators , such as EvgA , YdeO , MnmE , GadE , GadX , CRP , and H-NS , are involved in the regulation of gadE-mdtEF operon ( Gong et al. , 2004 ; Ma et al. , 2004 ; Hirakawa et al. , 2006 ; Tramonti et al. , 2008 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23874328" target="_blank">23874328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Given the role of GadX in activating genes involved in glu-tamate-dependent AR , more speciﬁcally , the diminished induction in gadX mutants , the decrease in acid tolerance shown by gadX and gadX-gadW mutants was expected .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Data revealed that YdeO and GadX activate P3 , P2 and P3P2 , while GadE autoactivates P1 and represses P3 and P3P2 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>In contrast to the effect of YdeO and GadX on the P2 and P3 promoters , overexpression of GadE , as predicted , did not activate P2 , P3 or the combined P3 P2 fusions in Salmonella during exponential-growth ( Fig. 6A ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>All of the genes and operons identiﬁed in this study fulﬁll the criteria established for inclusion in the GadX regulon : they were all induced by acid and regulated by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX activates some of the YdeO-regulated genes but does not activate yhiEUV .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>Several genes induced by overexpression of YdeO and GadX overlapped ; however , yhiE was induced only by YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>Many of the YdeO-activated genes were also activated by GadX , whereas yhiEUV were induced only by YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>The fusions were transferred to Salmonella , which lacks this AR system , and plasmid-borne E. coli-speciﬁc regulators EvgA , YdeO , GadE and GadX were introduced .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>Our results suggest that the gad system is positively regulated by at least two AraC/XylS-type regulators , YdeO and GadX , and also suggest that EvgA and YdeO regulate acid resistance genes more globally than GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , even if we could not rule out some false positives , our results showed that several genes could be identiﬁed as signiﬁcantly induced at low pH , demonstrating that GadE and GadX act as transcriptional-activators of genes of the H-NS regulon under acidic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>This suggests that overexpression of either GadX or GadE alone , in an FB8 genetic background , is not sufﬁcient to induce expression of genes involved in the bacterial response to low pH when cells are grown at neutral pH. Overexpression of gadX signiﬁcantly induced the expression of 48 genes of the H-NS regulon ( Table 3a ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>This further supports a role for GadX in the positive regulation of genes involved in low pH response , especially in the presence of glutamate .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11298273" target="_blank">11298273</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , gel mobility shift assays demonstrated that GadE could be autoregulated , and regulated GadX , suggesting that an indirect effect of GadE on the transcriptional control of some of the target genes identiﬁed here could not be ruled out .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=14702398" target="_blank">14702398</a>]<br></li>
<li>On the other hand , genes encoding several transcriptional factors , such as Fur , RcsA , SoxS , and ZraR , are up-regu-lated , and others , such as GadE , GadX , GcvA , and MetR , are down-regu-lated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16418169" target="_blank">16418169</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , as indole obviously does not cause acidiﬁcation of the medium , our results indicate that GadX responds to indole even under non-acidic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , GadX appears to function as a transcriptional-activator under acidic conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>This can again be attributed to an increase in GadX levels , which leads to an increase in gadY transcription and indirectly affects gadW P2 promoter activity , and also a decrease in gadW transcription from the P1 promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>When H-NS repression is relieved , GadX levels increase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The observed increase in the gadW P1 transcript is probably due to the removal of GadX repression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The increase in the lower band could also be the result of increased gadW transcription due to increased GadX levels or could correspond to other gadX-gadW fragments derived from processing .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21147125" target="_blank">21147125</a>]<br></li>
<li>It can therefore be argued that GadX is not involved in activation of transcription arising from PgadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indeed , as GadX is synthesized and its concentration rises over a threshold level , it can successfully relieve H-NS repression at the gadA promoter ( as shown in Fig. 7A , a ratio GadX : H-NS ranging between 1:10 and 1:20 is required to alleviate the H-NS-dependent inhibition ) , further causing its own production from the dicistronic gadAX mRNA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>H-NS is still capable of repressing gadA transcription in the presence of low concentrations of GadX ( below 25 nM ) , thus significantly counteracting the GadX-dependent activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Furthermore , it is important to notice that the activation of gadA transcription by GadX in the absence of H-NS is not cooperative , whereas it shows a substantial degree of cooperativity in terms of effects in the presence of H-NS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , possible antagonistic effects between GadX and H-NS , resulting in activation/repression of gadA gene , have been investigated in vitro by monitoring promoter activity in the presence of both purified proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>This observation is in line with the finding that even at the highest GadX concentration tested , in vitro gadA promoter activity in the presence of H-NS never attains the values obtained with GadX alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Although gadA transcription is stimulated more than 2-fold by GadX alone and strongly repressed ( up to 70 % ) by H-NS alone , as also shown in Figs. 4 and 6 , the effect of simultaneously adding both proteins to the reaction mixture gives rise to the gadA transcription profiles shown in Fig. 7A .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>The GadX-dependent stimulation , without and with different amounts of H-NS , is more apparent when data from Fig. 7A are plotted as the relative increase ( - fold ) of gadA transcription versus GadX concentration ( Fig. 7B ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>The authors observed that the increase in gadA transcription , obtained as an indirect effect of counteracting H-NS inhibition , was greater than the direct stimulation of gadA transcription in the presence of GadX alone .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , the indirect effect , by counteracting H-NS inhibition , is more productive than the direct stimulation of gadA promoter activity by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>The signal GTPase MnmE is required for P2 expression in LB glucose The induction of gadE , gadA/BC , and AR all exhibit RpoS and GadX dependence during growth in LB medium , but become independent of both when grown in glucose-supplemented LB ( Castanie-Cornet et al. , 1999 ; Gong et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>The cAMP receptor protein ( CRP ) also plays a role in this RpoS-GadX pathway by tempering expression of RpoS during growth under conditions that result in high cAMP levels ( Ma et al. , 2003b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>Elevated RpoS levels , in turn , increase expression of GadX , which increases expression of gadE ( Zhou and Gottesman , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>That the degree of increase in the expression levels of regulator genes was relatively lower than that of mdtEF ( 41-fold ) may be due to the fact that GadX acts as a dimer in transcriptional regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcriptional-regulator GadX also induces gadE expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21193607" target="_blank">21193607</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since GadX is a known transcriptional-regulator [ 14-16 ,18,19,42 ] , the decrease in BtuB expression is due to its transcriptional repression by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21314918" target="_blank">21314918</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of this small RNA is highly induced during stationary phase in a manner that is dependent on the alternative sigma factor S. Overexpression of the three GadY RNA forms resulted in increased levels of the mRNA encoding the GadX transcriptional-activator , which in turn caused increased levels of the GadA and GadB glutamate decarboxylases .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15466020" target="_blank">15466020</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since indole induces the expression of mdtEF via transcriptional-regulator GadX ( 5 ) , we examined whether the growth-phase-dependent induction of mdtEF is mediated by gadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>In summary , the growth-phase-dependent control of mdtEF was mediated through modiﬁcation of the amounts of RpoS-dependent small-RNA GadY and transcriptional-regulator GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>Growth phase-dependent elevation of mdtEF expression was found to be mediated by the stationary-phase factor rpoS and the RpoS-dependent signaling pathway , Hfq , GadY , and GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX , Hfq , and RpoS are essential for indole-induced mdtEF expression , and the expression is induced via rpoS , gadY , and gadX up-regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>This would mean that the intracellular GadX level is sufﬁcient to activate transcription of the chromosomal copies of the gad structural genes , including gadC , resulting in increased expression of the GadC antiporter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>We provide evidence that GadX is a DNA-binding protein which recognizes the promoters of gadA and gadBC genes to a different extent and that GadX expression results in upregulation of target genes during exponential-growth in rich neutral medium , i.e. , when the gad system is normally repressed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>To correlate GadX expression with the upregulation of gad structural genes , we expressed the gadX gene under the control of the heterologous T5-lacO promoter-operator element and monitored transactivation of gad structural genes under conditions in which the gad genes are not expressed , i.e. , during exponential-growth in LB medium at pH 7.4 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Many AraC-like regulators bind ligands that alter their function ( 5 ) , but whether or not GadX or GadW binds speciﬁc cytoplasmic ligands remains unknown .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Glucose induction of P3 and P3P2 is independent of YdeO , GadXW , EvgAS and Crp We then asked whether any of the E. coli-speciﬁc regulators YdeO , GadX , GadW or EvgAS were needed for glucose-dependent induction of P3P2 -- lacZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX and GadW appear to play a role in gadE induction regardless of whether glucose is present in the growth medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX is known to induce various genes including gadA , hdeAB and yhiE under low pH conditions ( Masuda and Church , 2003 ; Ma et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>RcsB-dependent regulation of gadABC is not mediated by the regulation of gadEWX genes The expression of gadA and gadBC is regulated by a complex network involving notably the GadE , GadW and GadX regulators ( Ma et al. , 2003 ; see Foster , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
<li>The resulting increase in GadX somehow activates gadA and gadBC ( Giangrossi et al. , 2005 ; Ma et al. , 2002 ; Shin et al. , 2001 ; Tramonti et al. , 2002 , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Microarray studies indicate that GadX may actually activate gadE , which , in turn , would activate gadA and gadBC ( Hommais et al. , 2004 ; Tucker et al. , 2003 ; Weber et al. , 2005 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC-like regulator GadX , for example , is needed to activate the gadA/BC genes only when cells are grown in complex media , not in minimal salts media ( 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12867448" target="_blank">12867448</a>]<br></li>
<li>The AraC-family regulators GadX and GadW , previously found to activate gadA/BC in vitro , are now shown in vivo to directly activate gadE expression , which , in turn , activates the gadA/BC genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The goal is to increase the production of the GadX regulator , which , in turn , activates gadA/BC expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX transcriptionally activates GadA and GadB expression , and some studies suggest that GadW acts as a repressor to oppose this action ( 24 , 27 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15466020" target="_blank">15466020</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX activates expression from PgadA , while GadW inhibits expression ( in the presence of GadX ) from PgadA and PgadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Within the S-dependent circuit during the stationary phase of growth , either in rich or in minimal medium , the increase in gadA and gadBC transcription requires GadX , which directly binds the gadA and gadB regulatory regions and , under some circumstances , acts in combination with GadW ( 8 -- 12 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>This hypothesis is supported by the ﬁnding that in minimal medium under fermentative growth conditions and independent of the pH , GadW repression of gadA and gadBC is not due to inhibition of GadX and the latter protein is responsible for gadW repression ( 20 , 38 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16980449" target="_blank">16980449</a>]<br></li>
<li>Consistent with this interpretation , the abundance of transcripts encoding the acid-responsive regulators of gadA , gadBC , and hdeAB expression , GadE and GadX , decreased as aerobiosis increased ( Tables 3 and 7 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21252224" target="_blank">21252224</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX regulates the acid resistance genes gadA , gadBC , and hdeABD ( 12 ) , which were also induced by EvgA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12399493" target="_blank">12399493</a>]<br></li>
<li>Overexpression of either EvgA or GadX induced the expression of gadA , gadBC , and hdeABD .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12399493" target="_blank">12399493</a>]<br></li>
<li>Another unusual aspect of GadW is seen in Fig. 6A and B. Whereas removing GadW allowed GadX to activate gadA-lacZ expression at both growth pH values , removing GadX allowed W to activate expression only at pH 8 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Unlike LB , where they were needed to activate gadA/BC , GadX and GadW acted as negative regulators in minimal media ( in exponential phase ) such that removing them allowed additional , acid-induced expression ( Fig. 1E , lanes 1 and 2 versus 3 and 4 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , when GadW was removed through mutation , GadX activated gadA and gadBC expression under acid or alkaline conditions ( Fig. 2A , lanes 5 and 6 versus lanes 7 and 8 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , the mechanism by which GadX activates gadA and gadB is unclear .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>One model , discussed brieﬂy above , is that GadW might bind gadA and gadBC promoters best when cells are grown at pH 8 , which either prevents GadX from binding or attenuates GadX activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>It seems that , while either GadX or GadW can induce gadA and gadBC , when both AraC-like regulators are present , they inhibit each other 's function .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>It represses the expression of gadX and inhibits the activation of gadA and gadBC by GadX [ 15,18,27 ] .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21314918" target="_blank">21314918</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX levels increase and overcome repression of gadA and gadBC by GadW .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX , however , activates only gadA and gadBC expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadW clearly represses gadX and , in situations where GadX is missing , activates gadA and gadBC .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , when GadX is missing , GadW could inadvertently activate gadA and gadBC expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>An interesting question is why does GadW , in the absence of GadX , activate gadA and gadBC only at pH 8 ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , GadX serves as an activator of gadA and gadBC , while GadW can inhibit activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadW inhibits activation of gadA and gadBC by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , GadW is a negative regulatory protein that inhibits the activation of gadA and gadBC by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Results we report elsewhere indicate that GadW inhibits the GadX-dependent activation of gadA and gadBC transcription , yet GadW activates their transcription in the absence of GadX ( 14 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX activates expression of gadA and gadBC at any pH , while GadW inhibits GadX-dependent activation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , we propose a complex regulatory cascade in which global regulators ( RpoS , CRP , HN-S , EvgA , etc. ) inﬂuence the expression levels and/or activities of GadX and GadW , which in turn activate the expression and/or activities of transcription activators ( e.g. , YdeO and YhiE ) that directly activate subsets of target genes involved in AR .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>The gadA/BC genes , activated in response to acid stress and in stationary phase cells , are subjected to complex circuits of regulation involving 70 , S , cAMP receptor protein , H-NS , EvgAS , TorRS , GadE , GadX , GadW , and YdeO .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>Transcription of hdeAB depends on complex circuits of regulation involving RpoD ( 70 ) , RpoS ( 38 ) , H-NS , cyclic AMP receptor protein , GadE , GadX , GadW , GadY , EvgAS , YdeO , Lrp , MarA , SoxRS , TorRS , and TrmE , among other regulators ( see Fig. 1 and references in the legend ; see Fig. 2 for the DNA binding sites of some of these regulators in the hdeAB promoter ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the merodiploid strain , GadX and + GadW stimulate the wild-type gadE allele , and the resulting GadE protein activates the 2360 and 2195 gadE -- lacZ fusions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadW , though less effective than GadX , still activated gadE -- lacZ between four - and fivefold .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Moreover , repression of hdeAB by MarA was greater in the absence of GadX or Lrp in exponential phase at pH 7.0 and in the absence of GadW or RpoS in stationary phase at pH 5.5 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>In turn , MarA enhanced repression of hdeAB by H-NS and hindered activation by GadE in stationary phase and also reduced the activity of GadX , GadW , RpoS , and Lrp on hdeAB under some conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>Promoters P3 and P2 can be activated by GadX and GadW during growth to stationary phase , or by YdeO during log-phase growth in minimal medium below pH 7 .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadE was the main activator of hdeAB in LB medium under all the conditions studied , whereas GadX repressed or activated hdeAB depending on the growth conditions , and GadW repressed hdeAB .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>The different effects that GadX and GadW had under diverse conditions , sometimes opposite to that of GadE , support the idea that they can regulate hdeAB independently of GadE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX and GadW initially appeared to activate and repress the core gad genes , depending on the situation ( 13 , 25 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15489450" target="_blank">15489450</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX and GadW have been reported to activate and repress these promoters under different conditions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">GadX protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>The b-galactosi-dase activity of cells containing pCB1285lacZ and pGadXY , pGadX , or pGadY was compared to those containing pGAD10 and pCB1285lacZ .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21314918" target="_blank">21314918</a>]<br></li>
<li>If the T25-GadX and GadX-T18 hybrids dimerize in vivo , the two CyaA fragments will be brought together , reconstituting an active adenylate cyclase .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12446650" target="_blank">12446650</a>]<br></li>
