<li>B. Sequence alignment of the GadX and GadW binding sites in the gadA , gadBC , gadY , hdeAB , slp and gadE regulatory regions .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>DNase I footprinting analyses conﬁrmed that a 42 bp GadX / GadW binding site , which matched the consensus sequence 5 - WANDNCTDWTWKTRAYATWAWMATG KCTGATNTTTWYNTYAK-3 , is also present in the regulatory region of the slp-yhiF , hdeAB and gadE-mtdEF operons , all of which belong to the AFI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also showed for the ﬁrst time that GadX and GadW speciﬁcally bind to a 42 bp sequence that is found in ﬁve of the eight 5 ′ regulatory regions of the AFI .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The binding site of GadX in the hdeAB 5 ′ regulatory region ( Fig. 12B ) spans positions -87 to -46 on the coding strand and positions -79 to -47 on the noncoding strand , relative to the hdeAB transcriptional start site ( Arnqvist et al. , 1994 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The 42-bp-long GadX/GadW binding site clearly arises from the tandem arrangement of two 21 bp sequences , which were analysed separately in the ﬁnal consensus because we hypothesized that the binding of each monomer in the functional GadX ( and/or GadW ) dimer does not necessarily occur with similar affinity and/or strength at each site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The position of the GadX ( GadW ) binding site , centered 110 bp from the gadA transcriptional start site , is compatible with a model in which GadX and GadW contact this promoter as class I activators , i.e. , activators that bind to a site upstream of the promoter 35 element and contact the C-terminal domain of the subunit of RNA polymerase , thereby recruiting the polymerase to the promoter ( 3 , 35 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16980449" target="_blank">16980449</a>]<br></li>
<li>In this study , we identiﬁed a new 41 bp GadX / GadW binding site that was centred 41.5 bp upstream of the gadY ( 105 ) transcriptional start site .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The newly identiﬁed GadX and GadW binding site , centered at 220.5 bp upstream of the transcription start site of gadBC , is consistent with the hypothesis that stimulation of transcription mediated by these two regulators may occur through a DNA looping mechanism ( for a review , see reference 26 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16980449" target="_blank">16980449</a>]<br></li>
<li>The length of the binding site already suggested that GadX ( or GadW ) binds as a dimer ( Tramonti et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The length of the binding site suggests that GadW and GadX bind as dimers to the gadA promoter region , with the recognition helix of each of the four helix-turn-helix motifs occupying one of four consecutive DNA major grooves .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16980449" target="_blank">16980449</a>]<br></li>
<li>It should be noted , however , that a version of this site ( TGGCAAatTaGCCA ) is also located at -55 bp from the start of the T3 transcript making it tempting to suggest this sequence might allow YdeO and GadX to activate both promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>As a member of the AraC protein family , GadX is expected to bind speciﬁc sequence motifs located within or in the proximity of the target promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX and GadW are both members of the AraC/XylS family ( PS01124 ) , which typically comprises ª300-amino-acid-long transcriptional regulators that bind an unusually extended 17 -- 21 bp sequence at target promoters via two helix -- turn -- helix ( HTH ) motifs localized within the 100-amino-acid-long C-terminal domain ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Therefore , we split each binding site into two ; each half-site ( shown in Fig. 11A ) was of sufficient length ( 21 bp ) to allow the binding of the two HTH motifs present in the C-terminal domain of a GadX ( or GadW ) monomer , as in the case of the AraC / XylS-like proteins ( Gallegos et al. , 1997 ; Egan , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
