<li>DacrB/pQEevgA DacrB/pQEevgA -- + -- + -- + + + + 4 64 125 8 > 125 > 16 000 > 16 000 > 16 000 62.5 128 8 8 8 8 DacrBDydeO/pQEevgA DacrBDydeO/pQEevgA D / acrB pQEydeO DacrB/pQEydeO DacrBDevgAS/pQEydeO DacrBDhdeA-D/pQEydeO DacrBDhdeD-yhiE/pQEydeO 4 4 4 4 Comparison of YdeO and GadX regulons It has been reported that overexpression of GadX , another member of the AraC/XylS transcriptional regulators , induces gadBC , hdeD and gadA ( Hommais et al. , 2001 ; Shin et al. , 2001 ; Tramonti et al. , 2002 ) , which were also induced by YdeO overexpression ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , overexpressing MalE-GadX successfully induced gadA and gadB in E. coli ( Giangrossi et al. , 2005 ; Gong et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , gadE-mtdEF belongs to the AFI and was shown to be controlled by GadX and GadW ( Kobayashi et al. , 2006 ; Sayed et al. , 2007 ) , while ybaST is not included in the AFI but is known to be signiﬁcantly induced under acidic conditions and to belong to the GadX -- GadW regulon ( Tucker et al. , 2002 ; 2003 ; Hommais et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effect of tolC deletion on multidrug resistance modulated by the GadX regulator The results described above indicate that the expression of a multidrug efﬂux pump may be induced by overexpression of gadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>]<br></li>
<li>Together , these data indicate that multidrug resistance conferred by the GadX regulator is due to increased expression of the mdtEF multidrug efﬂux genes .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>]<br></li>
<li>Based on these results , we suggest that GadX controls the intracellular levels of its own mRNA by positively affecting the expression of the small RNA GadY , which has been shown to act at the post-transcriptional level by stabilizing the 3 ′ - UTR of the gadX mRNA ( Opdyke et al. , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>Construction of plasmids for gene expression YdeO , YdeP , YhiE and GadX expression plasmids , pQEydeO , pQEydeP , pQEyhiE and pQEgadX , respectively , were constructed as follows .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12694615" target="_blank">12694615</a>]<br></li>
<li>To investigate the effect of GadX on btuB expression , pGadX was constructed as follows .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21314918" target="_blank">21314918</a>]<br></li>
<li>In order to characterize the RpoS-GadY ( Hfq ) - GadX signaling pathway , we measured the growth phase-dependent changes in the expression of the rpoS , gadY , hfq , and gadX genes by means of the - galactosidase reporter assay .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since indole induces the expression of mdtEF via transcriptional regulator GadX ( 5 ) , we examined whether the growth phase-dependent induction of mdtEF is mediated by gadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results indicate that indole controls mdtEF gene expression via increasing the amounts of RpoS , GadY , and GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>GlcNAc-induced mdtEF gene expression is mediated by neither the EvgSA-YdeO nor the RpoS-GadX signaling pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885453" target="_blank">16885453</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX , Hfq , and RpoS are essential for indole-induced mdtEF expression , and the expression is induced via rpoS , gadY , and gadX up-regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>whereas when the gadX , hfq , or rpoS gene was deleted , the expression of mdtEF was no longer increased by indole at all ( Fig. 7B ) ; therefore , the induction of mdtEF by indole is also mediated by the RpoS-GadY ( Hfq ) - GadX signaling pathway .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885437" target="_blank">16885437</a>]<br></li>
<li>Indole signalling to cause yhiE gene expression is transmitted via GadX As shown in Fig. 2C , the expression of the yhiE gene induced by indole was independent of the EvgSA system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>The induction of mdtE by indole is independent of the EvgSA two-component signal transduction system that regulates the mdtE gene , but mediated by GadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15686558" target="_blank">15686558</a>]<br></li>
<li>These results suggest that there are at least two independent pathways for the induction of mdtEF expression , that is , the indole-driven GadX pathway and the two-component system , EvgSA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16885453" target="_blank">16885453</a>]<br></li>
<li>( b ) Transcriptional fusions of the b1500-ydeO , gadE , gadBC , and asr gene promoters were constructed in the pLUX vector , and the response of each of these promoters to a shift from pH 7 to pH values ranging between 6.3 and 4.9 ( as well as a mock induction at pH 7 ) was assayed in an E. coli MG1655 wild-type genetic back ¬ GadX and GadW , along with the small regulatory RNA GadY , collaborate with RpoS to relieve H-NS-mediated repression of the system when cultures enter into stationary phase16 but have also been reported to have a role during low pH response .20,29 In addition , GadW is under direct control of the PhoPQ two-component system ,30 and it has been shown that EvgAS can cross-talk to PhoPQ via the connector protein encoded by b1500 ( also known as safA26 ) , which resides directly upstream of and in the same operon as YdeO .18,31 As a first step to building a mathematical description of this complex network , we wished to assess whether a dynamic approach to monitoring gene expression within the network was both feasible and valid and in particular whether such an approach would reveal any novel aspects of the network that had not been detected to date .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20603130" target="_blank">20603130</a>]<br></li>
<li>Such an autoregulatory loop would imply that expression of both GadA and GadX is coordinated and responsible for superinduction of the whole gad system ; primary stimuli ( stationary phase and acid ) acting on PgadX would lead to increased expression of GadX and , in turn , to an ampliﬁcation of the response through GadX-de-pendent activation of the gadAX and gadBC promoters .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Autoregulation of the whole gad system is inferred by the positive effect of GadX on the gadA promoter and gadAX cotranscription .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , the gadBC operon coding for both components ( glutamic acid decarboxylase and cognate antiporter ) , necessary for gad system functioning , is more stimulated than gadA by GadX , thereby providing a prompt response to the acid stress .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=15795232" target="_blank">15795232</a>]<br></li>
<li>YdeO is an AraC-like transcription factor , as are GadX and the product of the gadW gene , which lies immediately downstream of gadX .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12730179" target="_blank">12730179</a>]<br></li>
<li>Expression analysis of the gad gene system in the gadX mutant indicates that GadX is required for maximal expression during the stationary phase and acid induction , though it is not essential for basal expression of the system .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>It belongs to the AraC/XylS family of bacterial transcriptional regulators , known to be activators of functions as diverse as sugar catabolism , responses to stress , and virulence .43,44 Expression analysis of the gad gene system in the gadX mutant indicates that GadX is required for maximal expression during stationary phase and acid induction .45 We have previously found that GadX participates in the mdtEF induction by indole and growth phase .46 In addition to the roles of GadX in acid resistance , we found that it contributed to multidrug resistance in E. coli by activating the MdtEF multidrug efﬂux pump ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18297445" target="_blank">18297445</a>]<br></li>
<li>Evidence has recently emerged that the activation of the gad system is mediated by the GadX protein ( 17 , 30 , 34 ) , a member of the AraC/XylS family of transcriptional regulators ( 15 ) , encoded by the gadX gene ( formerly designated yhiX ) , located downstream of gadA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=11976288" target="_blank">11976288</a>]<br></li>
<li>At present , it is known that the expression of the essential regulator GadE , a LuxR-like protein that is encoded by the gadE gene and located in the AFI ( Fig. 1 ) , is under the control of three different activation circuits ( for review , see Foster , 2004 ) : ( i ) the EvgAS/YdeO-dependent circuit activates gadE during the exponential phase of growth in minimal medium ( pH 5.5 ) containing glucose and relies on the activity of both the EvgAS two-component system and the activator YdeO , a member of the AraC/XylS family of transcriptional regulators , ( ii ) the TrmE-dependent circuit activates gadE in the stationary phase in unbuffered LB medium containing glucose and relies on the activity of TrmE , an Era-like molecular switch GTPase , and ( iii ) the GadX/GadW-dependent circuit is required for gadE activation upon entry into the stationary phase in buffered LB medium and involves the transcriptional regulators GadX and GadW , the genes of which are located downstream of gadA and gadX respectively ( Fig. 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>When using the -222 / +121 gadX : : lacZ construct , which contains the entire gadX 5 ′ regulatory region ( Tramonti et al. , 2002 ; Giangrossi et al. , 2005 ) , we observed that the transcription of the gadX gene from its native promoter increases in the stationary phase but is not appreciably affected by the pH of the growth medium or any of the known regulators of the GadX/GadW-dependent circuit of activation in the gad system , such as GadX , GadW , GadE and RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>The data from the gadX : : lacZ transcriptional fusions indicate that transcription of the gadX gene from its own promoter is not signiﬁcantly affected by either the pH of the growth medium or any of the regulators of the gad system , such as GadX itself , GadW , GadE and RpoS .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18808381" target="_blank">18808381</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , during growth in glucose ( pH 5.5 ) , GadX and GadW activation of gadE was additive ( Fig. 2b ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>GadX and GadW appear to play a role in gadE induction regardless of whether glucose is present in the growth medium .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Elevated RpoS levels , in turn , increase expression of GadX , which increases expression of gadE ( Zhou and Gottesman , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=19220752" target="_blank">19220752</a>]<br></li>
<li>MarA seems also to compete functionally with GadX , GadW , RpoS , and Lrp under some conditions , which might ensure that hdeAB expression is not repressed more than needed .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=18083817" target="_blank">18083817</a>]<br></li>
<li>We also found that neither GadX nor GadW activated expression of the 2360 to +331 fusion , confirming that sequences upstream of 2360 are important for activation by these proteins ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>RpoS does not appear to activate gadE through a GadXW-independent pathway , since rpoS , DgadXW and rpoS DgadXW mutants are equally acid sensitive , and the overexpression of RpoS does not induce gadE in a DgadXW mutant ( data not shown ) The '' 360 to '' 804 region is required for GadX and GadW activation of gadE The intergenic region controlling gadE expression is large ( 798 bp ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>The transcriptional regulator GadX also induces gadE expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=21193607" target="_blank">21193607</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the fact that RpoS is not needed for gadE expression in glucose , yet GadX and GadW remain important , suggests the presence of an RpoS-independent route for gadX induction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>Effects of GadX and GadW on gadE expression in E. coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17660422" target="_blank">17660422</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , neither GadX nor GadW is required for gadE expression ( data not shown ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of ybaS is also under the control of GadX transcription factor ( Tucker et al. , 2003 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17919280" target="_blank">17919280</a>]<br></li>
<li>The expression of the gadAXW and gadBC operons varies , depending on the culture medium , growth phase and environmental pH. The balance of three transcription factors , GadE , GadX and GadW , is involved in this complex regulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17919280" target="_blank">17919280</a>]<br></li>
<li>As GadE is also required for stationary phase expression of gadA/BC We demonstrated previously that either GadX or GadW was required by stationary phase cells to express gadA / BC ( Ma et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12940989" target="_blank">12940989</a>]<br></li>
<li>RcsB-dependent regulation of gadABC is not mediated by the regulation of gadEWX genes The expression of gadA and gadBC is regulated by a complex network involving notably the GadE , GadW and GadX regulators ( Ma et al. , 2003 ; see Foster , 2004 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17185552" target="_blank">17185552</a>]<br></li>
